reviewText:
After Skyrim, I wasn't expecting a lot from this. I suppose the wildcard involved here is ZeniMax Online Studios, whom I'd never thought would've made an effort. What you have here is something that has much more in common with The Secret World, Dungeons & Dragons: Online, and Uru: Ages Beyond Myst than it does with WoW, Guild Wars 2, or Wildstar. I'll let that stand on its own.

Couple this with...

The genuine respect shown for people of all genders and body types in the character creation (I can make a fat lady with small breasts);

The overall endless depths and diversity of respectfully depicted culture and intrigue present (mostly thanks to Elder Scrolls lore);

The fact that progression is tied to story-arcs rather than compulsive number-building, and one will want to continue playing out of engagement with the story and a desire to see what happens next rather than a mindless addiction;

How uncompromisingly fun and without grind crafting and gathering is, especially when you take into account the many chests you can lockpick;

The huge number of interactive things (like lore books and lootable containers) which help make the world feel alive and more believable;

The chatty and characterful NPCs (esp. Razum-dar) that always have something relevant and intelligent to say (versus the puerile nonsense that's usually trotted out);

The presence of choice and consequence (even if it is mostly cosmetic);

The stunning fact that they support visually disabled people by having everything (everything!) voice-acted to a level which is matched solely by TSW, and then only just;

The diversity allowed in character building, in that it's almost a freeform system (I honestly wish they'd just drop the classes and make them extra trees, then it would be freeform without err on par with TSW);

That there's penalties for being an absolute dirty-behind of a person (so if you steal and kill friendly NPCs, you'll have a bounty on your head that even other players can collect);

The wise choice of having three factions, which does much to dispel the Us vs. Them toxicity that's so pervasive in MMOs that have PvP;

That you can wander, roleplay, and have fun without feeling pressured;

The absence of raids means that people don't rush through the game, and that the journey hasn't been forsaken in favour of 'the game is fun when you get to the end of it' nonsense;

That it's so determined to distance itself from an MMO that it doesn't even have an auction house, since it doesn't want to promote grinding in any way;

And so much more.

It's not Uru. It's not The Secret World. And I'm not sure if I'd even put it above Dungeons & Dragons: Online. But if you've played all of the prior to death, and you're looking for a fun world where you can roleplay, do your own thing, and not be punished for that? Then this is the game for you. It's almost politically correct in how much of an MMO it isn't. And I dig it for that.

It could use more puzzles, puzzle-dungeons, and intrigue/mystery-based plotlines to really keep one on the edge of one's seat, and it could also use a full body in first person view to complete the sense of immersion, but even with these caveats mentioned it's still surprisingly great. It's not quite met its potential, but it's better than most of the garbage out there. This one can say he likes being a khajiit in it.

It's not like Skyrim. It's not like an MMO. If anything, it's like Oblivion, yet with its own pros and cons versus that game. And at the end of the day, even though I wasn't expecting to like this, I actually do. I like this and I feel I can recommend it in good conscience. Not many MMOs I can say that about (barring Uru, DDO, and TSW).

So there you go.

